48.","1410–1459":"1410–1459.","1448":"1448.","1459":"1459.","1 January 1448":"1. siječnja 1448.","1465":"1465.","1410":"1410","1 January 1493":"1. siječnja 1493.","1493":"1493.","1490":"1490.","1406":"1406","1439":"1439","1559":"1559","Hadleigh, Suffolk England, United Kingdom":"Hadleigh, Suffolk, Engleska, United Kingdom","Lympne, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Lympne, Kent, Engleska, United Kingdom","England":"England","Norfolk England":"Norfolk, Engleska, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"1 January 1448–1493":"1. ledna 1448–1493","1448–1493":"1448–1493","1439–1493":"1439–1493","1490–1559":"1490–1559","1406–1448":"1406–1448","1410–1459":"1410–1459","1448":"1448","1459":"1459","1 January 1448":"1. ledna 1448","1465":"1465","1410":"1410","1 January 1493":"1. ledna 1493","1493":"1493","1490":"1490","1406":"1406","1439":"1439","1559":"1559","Hadleigh, Suffolk England, United Kingdom":"Hadleigh, Suffolk, Anglie, United Kingdom","Lympne, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Lympne, Kent, Anglie, United Kingdom","England":"Anglie","Norfolk England":"Norfolk, Anglie, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1 January 1448–1493":"1. januar 1448–1493","1448–1493":"1448–1493","1439–1493":"1439–1493","1490–1559":"1490–1559","1406–1448":"1406–1448","1410–1459":"1410–1459","1448":"1448","1459":"1459","1 January 1448":"1. januar 1448","1465":"1465","1410":"1410","1 January 1493":"1. januar 1493","1493":"1493","1490":"1490","1406":"1406","1439":"1439","1559":"1559","Hadleigh, Suffolk England, United Kingdom":"Hadleigh, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Lympne, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Lympne, Kent, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Norfolk England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1 January 1448–1493":"1 januari 1448–1493","1448–1493":"1448–1493","1439–1493":"1439–1493","1490–1559":"1490–1559","1406–1448":"1406–1448","1410–1459":"1410–1459","1448":"1448","1459":"1459","1 January 1448":"1 januari 1448","1465":"1465","1410":"1410","1 January 1493":"1 januari 1493","1493":"1493","1490":"1490","1406":"1406","1439":"1439","1559":"1559","Hadleigh, Suffolk England, United Kingdom":"Hadleigh, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lympne, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Lympne, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Norfolk England":"Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1 January 1448–1493":"1 January 1448–1493","1448–1493":"1448–1493","1439–1493":"1439–1493","1490–1559":"1490–1559","1406–1448":"1406–1448","1410–1459":"1410–1459","1448":"1448","1459":"1459","1 January 1448":"1 January 1448","1465":"1465","1410":"1410","1 January 1493":"1 January 1493","1493":"1493","1490":"1490","1406":"1406","1439":"1439","1559":"1559","Hadleigh, Suffolk England, United Kingdom":"Hadleigh, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Lympne, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Lympne, Kent, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Norfolk England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Cheng, Jing, Kam Fung, Wai Shing, Wing, Yali, Yuk.","Chinese:","variant Romanization of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Ou","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Ying, Ching, Heng, Hong, Jia, Kuang Yu, Li-Ching, Cho, Chong, Chung, Sa.  Southeast Asian Lichun, Ming, Quan, Roeun, Sokhom, Chau, Hai, Leang, Ly, Nhanh, Phan, Pho, Tha.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 歐, meaning ‘to sing someone's praise’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the placename Dong Ou (東甌), a fief (in present-day Wenzhou in Zhejiang province) which was granted to Yao in 192  BC . It is said that Yao was a descendant of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the placename Ou Yu (歐餘), the name of a fief (located in present-day Zhejiang province) that was granted to Ti, the second son of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 區, originally denoting an ancient vessel for measurement in ancient Chinese: from the personal name of <i>Ou Zhizi</i> (歐治子), an expert sword-maker who lived during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). Some of his descendants inherited <i>Ou</i> (歐) as their surname, simplifying the Chinese character 歐 to 區."]}]},{"name":"Beddingfield","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Suffolk): habitational name from Bedingfield in Suffolk. The placename is recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Bedingefelda</i>, from the Old English personal name <i>Bēda</i> + the connective particle <i>-ing-</i> ‘associated with, named after’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country’."],"variants":[{"name":"Bedingfield","meanings":["English (Suffolk and Norfolk): variant of   Beddingfield  ."]}]},{"name":"Warren","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Warin</i>, <i>Werin</i>, a borrowing of ancient Germanic <i>Warino</i>, a short form of various compound names based on the element <i>warin</i> ‘protection, shelter’ or ‘guard’. Compare   Waring  .","English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from La Varrenne in Seine-Maritime, France, named with a Gaulish element probably descriptive of alluvial land or sandy soil. This was the name of a major Norman family after the Conquest. In Ireland, this name has been Gaelicized as <b>Bharain</b>.","Irish: adopted as an English form of Gaelic <b>Ó Murnáin</b> (see   Murnane  ,   Warner  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Warrens","meanings":["English: variant of   Warren   with genitival or excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Warrener","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): occupational name from Old French <i>warrennier</i> ‘warrener’, an officer employed to watch over game in a park or game preserve. Compare   Warren  ."]},{"name":"Murnane","meanings":["Irish (Munster): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Murnáin</b>, a shortened and dissimilated form of <b>Ó Manannáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Manannán</i>’, name borne in Celtic mythology by a sea god associated with the Isle of Man. All three syllables appear in the variant <b>Marrinan</b>. This name has also been Anglicized as   Warren   and   Warner  ."]},{"name":"Waren","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Warren  ."]},{"name":"Warne","meanings":["shortened form of   Warren  .","occasionally a habitational name from Wearne in Somerset. The place takes its name from a lost stream-name based on British <i>verno-</i> ‘alder, swamp’.","English:"]},{"name":"Waring","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Warren  , from the Norman personal name <i>Warin</i>, derived from ancient Germanic <i>Warino</i>, a short form of various compound names based on the element <i>warin</i> ‘protection, shelter’ or ‘guard’. The name was popular in France and among the Normans (see   Guerin  )."]}]},{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. If not simply an invention, it may have been devised as a feminine equivalent of   Alan   (of which it is an anagram), or a shortened form of   Alana .  It seems to have been first used by the American film actress  Lana Turner  (  1920–1995 ), whose original name was  Julia ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Agnes of Beddingfield Warren was born on 1 January 1448, in Hadleigh, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, her father, John Robert de Warren, was 42 and her mother, Dorothy Forth, was 39. She married Sir Charles Arthur de Vesey in 1465, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1493, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1 January 1448–1493":"1. jaanuar 1448–1493","1448–1493":"1448–1493","1439–1493":"1439–1493","1490–1559":"1490–1559","1406–1448":"1406–1448","1410–1459":"1410–1459","1448":"1448","1459":"1459","1 January 1448":"1. jaanuar 1448","1465":"1465","1410":"141